column1: #Text=SpaceX Crew Dragon capsule docks with International Space Station
#Text=On Sunday , the SpaceX Crew Dragon capsule successfully docked with the International Space Station in orbit around the Earth .

#Text=Although the Crew Dragon was carrying only cargo and a mannequin equipped with sensors , this was the first time since the retirement of the space shuttles in 2011 a United States spacecraft capable of carrying humans has made it to the station .
#Text=Artist 's rendition of the Crew Dragon en route .
#Text=Most of the docking process was automatic by the capsule , though the crew of the ISS were able to send the capsule commands to perform simple movements .
#Text=Previous SpaceX pods have relied on the station 's own robotic arm apparatus to take hold of them .

#Text=At 2:49 a.m. local time ( 7:49 a.m. UTC ) on Saturday morning , the Crew Dragon was launched via a Falcon 9 rocket from the Kennedy Space Center at Cape Canaveral , Florida in the southeastern United States .
#Text=Crew Dragon has enough room for seven people but on this occasion carried only a mannequin , nicknamed " Ripley " for Sigourney Weaver 's character in the film Alien .
#Text=The Crew Dragon is scheduled to remain at the station during the week and return to Earth on Friday .
#Text=Bill Gerstenmaier of NASA spoke of the collaboration between his agency and SpaceX : " It 's fun working with a new partner that approaches the problem in a slightly different way .
